Morris established a new Michigan single-season [[assist (basketball)|assist]]s record during the [[2011 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] (235 in 35 games).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/032011aaf.html|title=Postgame Notes: #3 Duke 73, Michigan 71|accessdate=2011-03-20|date=2011-03-20|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  The previous highest single-season assists totals in Michigan history were by [[Gary Grant]] (234 in 34 games, [[1987<U+2013>88 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1987<U+2013>88]]) and [[Rumeal Robinson]] (233 in 37 games, [[1988<U+2013>89 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1988<U+2013>89]]).<ref name=>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-records|title=All-Time Records|accessdate=2011-01-16|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com|page=6}}</ref> His average of 6.71 assists per game led the Big Ten Conference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2010-2011/confldrs.html|title=2010-11 Big Ten Conference: Conference Basketball Statistics|accessdate=2011-03-21|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> For the season, Morris also led the 2010&ndash;11 team in [[point (basketball)|points]] per game and [[steal (basketball)|steals]] per game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/team/stats/_/id/130/year/2011/michigan-wolverines|title=Michigan Wolverines Stats - 2010-11|accessdate=2011-03-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

Following the [[2010<U+2013>11 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season]], Darius Morris was selected as a third team All-Big Ten selection by both the conference's coaches and the conference's media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtennetwork.com/dpp/sports/basketball-mens/big-ten-releases-all-big-ten-teams-201137|title=Big Ten Releases All-Big Ten Teams: Purdue's Johnson named Player of the Year|accessdate=2011-03-08|date=2011-03-07|publisher=[[Big Ten Network]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/weekly-release.pdf|title=2010-11 All-Big Ten Men<U+2019>s Basketball Team|accessdate=2011-03-08|date=2011-03-07|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Morris was also a [[National Association of Basketball Coaches]] (NABC) Division I District 7 All<U+2010>District second team choice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nabc.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/nabc/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/D1AllDistrict2011|format=PDF| work=| publisher=[[National Association of Basketball Coaches]]| title=National Association of Basketball Coaches Announces 2011 Division I All-District Teams| accessdate=2011-03-10|date=2011-03-09}}</ref> Since the [[Big Ten Conference]] is its own district, this is equivalent to being named second team All-Big Ten by the NABC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nabc.org/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/nabc/sports/c-baskbl/auto_pdf/2008-09NABCDistrictRealignm|title=2008<U+2013>09 NABC Division I Men's Basketball: District Realignment|accessdate=2011-03-10|publisher=[[National Association of Basketball Coaches]]/[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>

Following the season, Morris sought the advice of the NBA's undergraduate advisory committee to determine his draft prospects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=6266825|title=Darius Morris asks for draft advice|accessdate=2011-03-28|date=2011-03-28|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On May 4, Morris announced his final decision not to withdraw his name prior to the May 8 deadline and to enter the June 23, [[2011 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/darius-morris-officially-leaves-michigan-basketball-to-try-for-the-nba/|title=Darius Morris officially leaves Michigan basketball for shot in the NBA|accessdate=2011-05-05|date=2011-05-04|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/former-michigan-guard-darius-morris-is-making-the-right-decision-leaving-for-the-nba/|title=Analysis: 5 reasons Darius Morris is making the right decision to leave Michigan for the NBA|accessdate=2011-05-05|date=2011-05-04|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/campusrivalry/post/2011/05/darius-morris-nba-draft-michigan-wolverines/1|title=Michigan's Darius Morris to remain in NBA draft|accessdate=2011-05-05|date=2011-05-04|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref> 
{{clear}}

==Pro career==
[[ESPN]]'s [[Chad Ford]] described Morris at a legit {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2}} as the biggest true point guard in the draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/lakers/post/_/id/20549/lakers-select-darius-morris-with-41st-pick|title=Lakers select Darius Morris with 41st pick (UPDATED)|accessdate=2011-06-24|date=2011-06-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Kamenetzky, Brian}}</ref> Morris was selected by his hometown Los Angeles Lakers with the 41st overall selection in the 2nd round of the [[2011 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-darius-morris-nba-draft/|title=Los Angeles native Darius Morris chosen by hometown Lakers in second round of NBA Draft|accessdate=2011-06-24|date=2011-06-23|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref>

